{{Short description|Comprehensive list of compounds structurally related to fentanyl}}
{{cs1 config|name-list-style=vanc}}
The following is a list of [[fentanyl]] [[Structural analog|analogues]] (sometimes referred to as '''fentalogs'''),<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hassanien SH, Bassman JR, Perrien Naccarato CM, Twarozynski JJ, Traynor JR, Iula DM, Anand JP | journal=Drug Testing and Analysis | title=In vitro pharmacology of fentanyl analogs at the human mu opioid receptor and their spectroscopic analysis | volume=12 | issue=8 | pages=1212–1221 | date= August 2020 | doi=10.1002/dta.2822| pmid=32415719 | pmc=8034271 }}</ref><ref>Vaughan SR, Fulton AC, DeGreeff LE. Comparative analysis of vapor profiles of fentalogs and illicit fentanyl. ''Anal Bioanal Chem'' 413, 7055–7062 (2021). {{doi|10.1007/s00216-021-03670-4}}</ref><ref name="pmid34957817">{{cite journal | vauthors = Patel JC, Parveen S | title = In Vitro and In Vivo Analysis of Fentanyl and Fentalog Metabolites using Hyphenated Chromatographic Techniques: A Review | journal = Chemical Research in Toxicology | volume = 35 | issue = 1 | pages = 30–42 | date = January 2022 | pmid = 34957817 | doi = 10.1021/acs.chemrestox.1c00225 | s2cid = 245500557 }}</ref> and includes both compounds developed by pharmaceutical companies for legitimate medical use, and those which have been sold as [[designer drug]]s. The latter have been reported to national drug control agencies such as the [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]], and some to transnational agencies such as the [[EMCDDA]] and [[UNODC]].<ref name=pmid25976511>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mounteney J, Giraudon I, Denissov G, Griffiths P | title = Fentanyls: Are we missing the signs? Highly potent and on the rise in Europe | journal = The International Journal on Drug Policy | volume = 26 | issue = 7 | pages = 626–31 | date = July 2015 | pmid = 25976511 | doi = 10.1016/j.drugpo.2015.04.003 }}</ref><ref name=pmid28713291>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zawilska JB | title = An Expanding World of Novel Psychoactive Substances: Opioids | journal = Frontiers in Psychiatry | volume = 8 | article-number = 110 | year = 2017 | pmid = 28713291 | pmc = 5492455 | doi = 10.3389/fpsyt.2017.00110 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.unodc.org/documents/scientific/Recommended_methods_for_the_identification_and_analysis_of_Fentanyl.pdf | title = Recommended Methods for the Identification and Analysis of Fentanyl and its Analogues in Biological Specimens. | work = United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime | date = November 2017}}</ref><ref name=pmid24635521>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vardanyan RS, Hruby VJ | title = Fentanyl-related compounds and derivatives: current status and future prospects for pharmaceutical applications | journal = Future Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 6 | issue = 4 | pages = 385–412 | date = March 2014 | pmid = 24635521 | pmc = 4137794 | doi = 10.4155/fmc.13.215 }}</ref><ref name=pmid29042317>{{cite journal | vauthors = Armenian P, Vo KT, Barr-Walker J, Lynch KL | title = Fentanyl, fentanyl analogs and novel synthetic opioids: A comprehensive review | journal = Neuropharmacology | volume = 134 | issue = Pt A | pages = 121–132 | date = May 2018 | pmid = 29042317 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuropharm.2017.10.016 | s2cid = 21404877 | url = http://www.escholarship.org/uc/item/8xh0s7nf | url-access = subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.incb.org/documents/Global_Projects_OPIOIDS/2018_June_24_INCB.OPIOIDS.Fentanyl_without_known_uses.pdf | title = Fentanyl-related substances with no known legitimate uses. | work = International Narcotics Control Board | date = 24 June 2018 }}</ref><ref name="pmid35049654">{{cite journal | vauthors = Choińska MK, Šestáková I, Hrdlička V, Skopalová J, Langmaier J, Maier V, Navrátil T | title = Electroanalysis of Fentanyl and Its New Analogs: A Review | journal = Biosensors | volume = 12 | issue = 1 | date = January 2022 | page = 26 | pmid = 35049654 | pmc = 8774265 | doi = 10.3390/bios12010026 | doi-access = free }}</ref> This is not a comprehensive or exhaustive list of fentanyl analogues, as more than 1400 compounds from this family have been described in the scientific and patent literature.<ref name="pmid1875771">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bagley JR, Kudzma LV, Lalinde NL, Colapret JA, Huang BS, Lin BS, Jerussi TP, Benvenga MJ, Doorley BM, Ossipov MH | display-authors = 6 | title = Evolution of the 4-anilidopiperidine class of opioid analgesics | journal = Medicinal Research Reviews | volume = 11 | issue = 4 | pages = 403–36 | date = July 1991 | pmid = 1875771 | doi = 10.1002/med.2610110404 | s2cid = 33000913 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.forensicscience.pl/pfs/59_skulska.pdf | vauthors = Skulska A, Kała M, Parczewski A | title = Fentanyl and its analogs in the forensic laboratory. Medical and analytical problems. | journal = Probl Forensic Sci | date = 2004 | volume = 59 | pages = 127–42 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Misailidi N, Papoutsis I, Nikolaou P, Dona A, Spiliopoulou C, Athanaselis S | title = Fentanyls continue to replace heroin in the drug arena: the cases of ocfentanil and carfentanil | journal = Forensic Toxicology | volume = 36 | issue = 1 | pages = 12–32 | date = January 2018 | pmid = 29367860 | pmc = 5754389 | doi = 10.1007/s11419-017-0379-4 }}</ref><ref name="pmid31024296">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wilde M, Pichini S, Pacifici R, Tagliabracci A, Busardò FP, Auwärter V, Solimini R | title = Metabolic Pathways and Potencies of New Fentanyl Analogs | journal = Frontiers in Pharmacology | volume = 10 | article-number = 238 | date = 2019 | pmid = 31024296 | pmc = 6461066 | doi = 10.3389/fphar.2019.00238 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name="pmid31504606">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sofalvi S, Lavins ES, Brooker IT, Kaspar CK, Kucmanic J, Mazzola CD, Mitchell-Mata CL, Clyde CL, Rico RN, Apollonio LG, Goggin C, Marshall B, Moore D, Gilson TP | display-authors = 6 | title = Unique Structural/Stereo-Isomer and Isobar Analysis of Novel Fentanyl Analogues in Postmortem and DUID Whole Blood by UHPLC-MS-MS | journal = Journal of Analytical Toxicology | volume = 43 | issue = 9 | pages = 673–687 | date = October 2019 | pmid = 31504606 | doi = 10.1093/jat/bkz056 | doi-access = free }}</ref> However, this list does include many notable compounds that have reached late-stage human clinical trials, and compounds which have been sold as designer drugs, as well as representative examples of significant structural variations reported in the scientific and patent literature. The structural variations among fentanyl analogues can impart profound pharmacological differences between each other, especially regarding potency and efficacy.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Varshneya NB, Walentiny DM, Moisa LT, Walker TD, Akinfiresoye LR, Beardsley PM | title = Opioid-like antinociceptive and locomotor effects of emerging fentanyl-related substances | journal = Neuropharmacology | volume = 151 | pages = 171–179 | date = June 2019 | pmid = 30904478 | pmc = 8992608 | doi = 10.1016/j.neuropharm.2019.03.023 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Varshneya NB, Walentiny DM, Moisa LT, Walker TD, Akinfiresoye LR, Beardsley PM | title = Fentanyl-related substances elicit antinociception and hyperlocomotion in mice via opioid receptors | journal = Pharmacology, Biochemistry, and Behavior | volume = 208 | article-number = 173242 | date = September 2021 | pmid = 34302853 | pmc = 9044821 | doi = 10.1016/j.pbb.2021.173242 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Varshneya NB, Hassanien SH, Holt MC, Stevens DL, Layle NK, Bassman JR, Iula DM, Beardsley PM | display-authors = 6 | title = Respiratory depressant effects of fentanyl analogs are opioid receptor-mediated | journal = Biochemical Pharmacology | volume = 195 | article-number = 114805 | date = January 2022 | pmid = 34673011 | pmc = 9022371 | doi = 10.1016/j.bcp.2021.114805 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Varshneya NB, Walentiny DM, Stevens DL, Walker TD, Akinfiresoye LR, Beardsley PM | title = Structurally diverse fentanyl analogs yield differential locomotor activities in mice | journal = Pharmacology, Biochemistry, and Behavior | volume = 222 | article-number = 173496 | date = January 2023 | pmid = 36435268 | pmc = 9845183 | doi = 10.1016/j.pbb.2022.173496 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Varshneya NB, Hassanien SH, Holt MC, Stevens DL, Layle NK, Bassman JR, Iula DM, Beardsley PM | display-authors = 6 | title = Fentanyl analog structure-activity relationships demonstrate determinants of diverging potencies for antinociception and respiratory depression | journal = Pharmacology, Biochemistry, and Behavior | volume = 226 | article-number = 173572 | date = May 2023 | pmid = 37236405 | pmc = 10326888 | doi = 10.1016/j.pbb.2023.173572 }}</ref>

In the United States, the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) placed the class of "Fentanyl-Related Substances" on the [[List of Schedule I drugs (US)|list of Schedule I drugs]] in 2018, making it illegal to manufacture, distribute, or possess fentanyl analogs, with very broad terminology being used in its scheduling.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Schedules of Controlled Substances: Temporary Placement of Fentanyl-Related Substances in Schedule I. Temporary amendment; temporary scheduling order | journal = Federal Register | volume = 83 | issue = 25 | pages = 5188–92 | date = February 2018 | pmid = 29932611 | author = Drug Enforcement Administration | publisher = Department of Justice }}</ref> Regarding the temporary control of fentanyl-related substances, Schedule I was extended through December 31, 2024 by Public Law 117-328.<ref>{{Cite web | work = Drug Enforcement Administration, Diversion Control Division, Drug & Chemical Evaluation Section. | publisher = Department of Justice  |date=January 2023 |title=Fentanyl-Related Substances |url=https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/drug_chem_info/frs.pdf}}</ref>

